events.name: Flutter Study Jam
events.description:
Details:

Flutter is Google‚Äôs mobile app SDK for crafting high-quality native interfaces on iOS and Android in record time. Flutter works with existing code, is used by developers and organizations around the world, and is free and open source.

Flutter Study Jams are Community-run study groups based on the Flutter Udacity Course. Participants learn how to use Flutter to develop high-quality, interactive mobile applications for iOS and Android devices.

Everyone, who completes the course will get a Google-offered Study Jam completion certificate and a profile badge.

The target audience for Flutter Study Jam:
1) Those just getting started with mobile app development
2) Those with programming experience on other mobile app frameworks.

Why be a part of this Study Jam?
-> Work with Google instructors step-by-step to build a fully functional native ‚ÄúUnit Converter App‚Äù for both iOS and Android using Flutter
-> Learn how to set up your environment and start building your first Flutter application
-> Learn about fundamentals: UI Widgets, App State, Material Design, User Interaction and Gestures, and Packages
-> Learn how to structure and architect your app and use Flutter's tooling to build apps efficiently

Complete the course and get Google-offered Study Jam completion certificate and a profile badge.

Note: Bring a laptop! The course will run on all of the latest versions of the popular browsers. For the best experience, the laptop should have Flutter installed on it prior to starting the study jam to save time. Windows/Linux/Mac would all be fine.

Check out : https://flutter.io/get-started/install/

If you have any problems installing flutter do not hesitate to send a message to the organizer. Alternatively we will help you get set up at the meet-up.

events.description:
**

RSVP here doesn't guarantee admission. To guarantee admission, buy tickets here: https://gdgburnabydevfest18.eventbrite.com/

Website: https://gdg-burnaby-web-app.firebaseapp.com/

**

GDG Burnaby, in collaboration with IEEE Vancouver CS Chapter brings to you it's biggest event- GDG DevFest'18.

This year we aim to bring together people who shape the future of ML, Web and Security technologies at 6 hours of sessions, workshops and networking. Described by many as 'Google I/O of Google Community Events', our team creates DevFest to be the best place for inspiration and experience sharing.

Speakers:
1.Kyle Hunslow

-Machine Learning Engineer and AI Tech Lead for Digitalist Vancouver Studio.

Session: Intro to Object Detection and Semantic Segmentation for Self Driving Car Applications

Kyle will introduce some popular Deep Learning and Computer Vision techniques currently used in the self-driving car industry. He'll outline the workflow for training Convolutional Neural Networks to perform object detection and semantic segmentation tasks. You'll get hands on experience with Tensorflow and Python through an interactive Jupyter Notebook session hosted in Google Colab. It is highly recommended that you follow along with the live coding session, so don't forget your laptop! Please prepare by signing up and getting familiar with Colab.

2. Sarah Kraynick

-CE0/Cyber Security Consultant -Social Engineer (Former- Women Techmakers Berlin)

Session: Who is in your pocket? Security and Privacy for Mobile Developers

With mobile and IoT devices proliferating at an exponential rate security is more important than ever. Sarah is here to discuss the threats and ways to mitigate these threats as a developer. This talk will mainly be focused on the Android OS and Android App development, though will also have lots to offer for those interested in mobile/IoT security as a whole.

3.Bob Gill

-Vice Chair, IEEE Computing Science Vancouver

Session : Sustainable Solution for Smart Cities

Bob has been associated will IEEE Vancouver more than 15 years now. In past he has served as the chair of IEEE Vancouver Section and is currently heading the Computing Science Section. He is a Fellow of Engineers Canada and has served APEGBC in various capacities and presently serving as a member on Mentoring committee. He will present some sustainable solutions for building the future smart city.

4. Cleo Espiritu: Google Developer Expert for G-Suite

Session: Transforming business processes with G-Suite and Google App Maker

Can we get "non-coders" to design and build apps with minimal assistance? Why would we want to do so? In this lightning talk, we will discuss how Google App Maker and Apps Script enables "citizen developers" to create solutions to transform their business processe

Keep yourself posted as we add more speakers! Want to buy tickets, checkout the link here:

events.description:
**New venue: Image Theatre, Robert C. Brown Hall (in the hallway of Academic Quadrangle), Simon Fraser University, Burnaby

** We highly recommend people to get a free ticket at Eventbrite: https://tensorflowworkshop.eventbrite.com so that, in case there are any changes in the room location, we can update you more conveniently. Having said that, you can RSVP on meetup if you would like to do so.**

**Our friends from Vancouver are hosting a talk by Martin on June 27th on the topic "Tensorflow, deep learning, and modern convolutional neural nets ". Find the details here: https://www.meetup.com/GDGCloudVancouver/events/262110468/ **
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
We are back again and this time with a workshop!

Machine learning, deep learning, neural networks, modeling, and learning are the buzz words in today's time. Be it at the scale of Boston Robotics or simple image recognition on our smartphones, we have heard of them time and again. Today, this work is being pushed forward by 'Tensorflow': end-to-end open source platform for machine learning (https://www.tensorflow.org/), the work which came out of 'Google Brain'. It is widely used in research labs by developers and those Ph.D. scholars across the world.

How much this sounds fascinating, wouldn't it be great if you get to do a 'hands-on' workshop on the TensorFlow, led by instructors who are creating the materials on the same?

Google Developers Burnaby in collaboration with IEEE SFU, brings to you a 3-hour 'hands-on' workshop on TensorFlow and Deep Learning. All beginners are welcome, even if you have never worked with TensorFlow at all. As the title suggests, get to know TensorFlow without even doing a Ph.D.

‚ú¶Title: 'TensorFlow without a Ph.D.': A workshop on TensorFlow and Deep Learning instructed by Martin Gorner, Google

‚ú¶Venue: Venue: Image Theatre, Robert C. Brown Hall (in hallway of Academic Quadrangle), Simon Fraser University, Burnaby

Note: If you are traveling to Burnaby, you can enter SFU from any bus loop, walk towards the Academic Quadrangle and look for Image Theatre (Robert C. Brown Hall). There will be few signs around to help you give directions.

‚ú¶Agenda:
‚Ä¢ 10:00 - 10:30- Meet and greet

‚Ä¢ 10:30 AM - 1:30 PM - Workshop on TensorFlow & Deep Learning
Theory + coding- neural network, gradient descent, dropout, overfitting, CNN, etc. Please note, you have to bring your laptops. We will be using Google Colab (https://colab.research.google.com/ ) for our workshop which is an online IDE for coding, hence you need not install anything on your laptop.

‚Ä¢ 1:30 PM - 2:00 PM- Q & A session

‚Ä¢ 2:00 PM: Event ends

We hope that you use this opportunity to get the first-hand experience or even better, dive deep into the knowledge of TensorFlow. Also, if you get time, talk to us (the organizers). We work with TensorFlow too and would be happy to talk about our work :)

events.name: X-POST:[NeuRIPS Special] Talks + Panel Discussion
events.description:
This event is organized by one of our friend meetups. To attend, RSVP here: https://www.meetup.com/Vancouver-Women-in-Machine-Learning-and-Data-Science/events/266670497/

NeuRIPS Conference' 2019 is happening in town and we are bringing them some of the domain experts to our meetup! Join us for 2 hours of talks, panel discussion and networking.
Agenda:

6:00 PM: Door opens, meet and greet

6:15 PM - 6:15 PM: Lightning Talk 1
Title: Deep Learning on Low resource Domains
Speaker: Ishadi Jayasingha (MSc,University of Moratuwa, Sri Lanka)

6:30 - 6:45 PM: Lightning Talk 2
Title: Lightning TalkPrivacy in Machine Learning
Speaker: Fatemehsadat Mireshghallah (Ph.D. student at UC San Diego)

6:45 PM: 7:00 PM: Lightning Talk 3:
Title: Fake News Detection via NLP is Vulnerable
Speaker: Meghana Moorthy (PhD Candidate of University of Ohio)

7:00 PM: 7:20 PM:Panel Discussion:
Panelists:
*Olga Vitek (Professor, Director - MS in Data Science Program
Khoury College of Computer Sciences, Northeastern University)

*Ioana Baldini (Research Staff Member at IBM T.J. Watson )

* TBA

7:20 PM - 8:00 PM: Networking
-------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

##About Speakers:

**Ishadi Jayasinghe**: Ishadi is an MSc research student from the University of Moratuwa, Sri Lanka. Her research contribution focuses on applying deep learning gin low-resource domain. She has designed an enhanced version of memory networks optimized for low resource domains (to be published by SOFSEM 2020). She has also worked with applicability of language in GANs for data augmentation tasks on low resource domains (to be published in SLAAI 2019). Currently, she working on designing a neural spell checker for Sinhala, a low resource language, but one of the main languages of Sri Lanka.

**Fatemehsadat Mireshghallah**: She a 2nd year CS Ph.D. student at UC San Diego. She received her B.Sc. in CSE with honors from Sharif University of Technology (Iran) in 2018. She works at the intersection of Machine Learning and System Privacy and applies self-supervision and variational inference to find distributions of noise that can best protect the sensitive content in data. She has presented her work at the SPML and PriML workshops in ICML19 and NeurIPS19, and has recently been accepted to ACM's ASPLOS20. Website: http://cseweb.ucsd.edu/~fmireshg/

**Meghana Moorthy**: Meghana is a Ph.D student at Ohio State University supervised by Prof.Srinivasan Parthasarathy. Last summer, she was a research intern at MILA under Prof.Laurent Charlin. Previously, she graduated with masters at UW-Madison. Her research interests are in NLP, Information Retrieval and graphical models.

**Olga Vitek**: Dr. Olga Vitek's research explores synergies between statistical science and ML, as applied to problems in analytical chemistry & systems biology. Her group designs experiments and analyzes data from investigations that rely on mass spectrometry & molecular imaging, to understand the functioning of living organisms. Her group contributes methods and open-source software. These include MSstats (R-based software for relative quantification of proteins in mass spectrometric experiments), Cardinal (R-based software for analyzing mass spectrometric images) and matter (memory-efficient reading, writing, and manipulation of binary larger-than-memory datasets in complex formats.)

**Ioana Baldini**: She a Research Staff Member at IBM T.J. Watson Research Center in the IBM Research AI organization. She is currently working on systems and tools that facilitate scientific discoveries. She is passionate about projects around Social Good and participates as a mentor in the Science for Social Good program. She got her Masters and PhD from University of Toronto.

events.name: Intro to Explainable AI
events.description:
**This event is in collaboration with Women In Machine Learning and Data Science, Vancouver. Please RSVP only on one page**

Abstract of the talk:

It seems like AI is everywhere these days, yet few people trust this technology, due in large part to black box algorithms, which prevent people‚Äîincluding the systems‚Äô creators‚Äîfrom knowing and understanding why such algorithms make recommendations and decisions. Left unchecked, this lack of transparency can lead to biased outcomes that put people and businesses at risk.

Luckily, there‚Äôs an answer to this problem: explainable AI‚Äîmachine learning that can be understood by and explained to those outside engineering.

In this talk, you‚Äôll learn how explainable AI‚Äôs more transparent nature decreases bias and increases trust in AI and leads teams toward interpretability by helping them predict how algorithms will behave. Whether you're trying to incorporate AI into your business or want to understand how algorithms make decisions, this course will help you quickly learn the core tenets of explainable AI, the cases for and against it, and how to use it in your own business.

About the speaker:

Dr. Lauren Maffeo leads business intelligence research at GetApp, which matches software shoppers with the right tools and technologies to grow their businesses. As an analyst, Lauren‚Äôs areas of interest include speech and natural language tools, data mining techniques, predictive analytics, and building a business case for data science.
